<subSubSection id="4AA8656BFFCCFFF3A9C0549197E8F8F5" pageId="7" pageNumber="40" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="020D36E0FFCCFFF3A9C0549197E8F8F5" pageId="7" pageNumber="40">
<emphasis id="30C6EAF2FFCCFFF3A9C054919243F961" bold="true" box="[199,287,1668,1693]" pageId="7" pageNumber="40">Biology</emphasis>
. All four known 
<taxonomicName id="C5B24D63FFCCFFF3A8EE549191D9F961" box="[489,645,1668,1693]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Blepharidatta" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="40" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="30C6EAF2FFCCFFF3A8EE549191D9F961" box="[489,645,1668,1693]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="40">Blepharidatta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species are generalist predators that nest in the ground or in the leaf litter; nests are single, short (up to 
<quantity id="CF2062D1DB075638973D2857CB8C47C0" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" unit="cm" value="20.0">20 cm</quantity>
) cylinders excavated in the ground or inside rolled leaves or rotting twigs, with one to 10 ergatoid gynes and up to 450 workers in the biggest colonies. Foragers patrol a roughly circular area around the single nest opening, where they collect live or dead arthropods to feed their larvae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
